<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   News Corp. Unit
   Is Seeking to Sell
   J.P. Lippincott Co.
   ----
   By Meg Cox
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<CO>
   NWS PCI
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Harper Collins Publishers, the book publishing
arm of Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., said it is putting J.P.
Lippincott Co. up for sale to reduce debt and focus Harper
Collins more tightly on book publishing.
   Publishing analysts said Lippincott, which publishes
specialized newsletters, journals and books on medical and
nursing topics, is believed to earn between $15 million and
$20 million a year on revenue of about $100 million. The
analysts said it could bring between $200 million and $250
million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   George Craig, president and chief executive officer of
Harper Collins, declined to comment on the sum Lippincott is
expected to fetch. But he said that in combination with
several other divestures made recently Harper Collins will
collect about $500 million in all. News Corp. has said it
plans asset sales of about that much to reduce the publishing
subsidiary's debt, which totals nearly $1 billion.
   Industry analysts said potential buyers include a number
of large, diversified media concerns, such as Paramount
Communications Inc. Paramount officials declined to comment.
Smaller publishing boutiques might also be buyers, such as
K-III Holdings, a year-old publishing concern headed by
William Reilly, ex-chief of Macmillan Inc., and financed by
Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts &amp; Co. "We're not in journals, and
we'd love to be," said Mr. Reilly. "It's a terrific
business."
   Mr. Craig said other recent divestitures by Harper Collins
include Gordon &amp; Gotch, a magazine distributor in New Zealand
and Australia, and the Angus &amp; Robertson Bookshops, a chain
of about 100 stores in Australia. There were several other
small properties, he said, which he didn't identify.
   Although Lippincott is quite profitable, "it is the
farthest away (of Harper's subsidiaries) from our mainstream
businesses," said Mr. Craig. "We've been evaluating our
portfolio recently and we decided to concentrate our efforts
on textbooks (elementary school through college), religious
books and general book publishing. We'll continue to grow and
we'll need money to grow."
   News Corp. has quickly built a huge book-publishing
empire, piling up debt along the way. In 1987, it acquired
Harper &amp; Row, a big but sleepy publishing house, for about
$300 million. News Corp. also bought a British publisher,
Collins; a religious publisher in the U.S., Zondervan; and
textbook publisher Scott, Foresman, for $407 million in
November.
   Mr. Craig said the sale of Lippincott is being conducted
by investment adviser Munroe Pofcher of New York. The
Philadelphia-based publishing company, founded in 1792, is
regarded as an established name in an area of publishing that
is steadier than general-interest trade books. Harper &amp; Row
bought Lippincott in 1978 for about $16 million and the
assumption of about $15 million in debt. Mr. Craig said it
has been quite profitable in recent years, growing in such
areas as electronic transmission of data to pharmacies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900413-0166
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900413-0166.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Overheated Economy
   In Taiwan Is Showing
   Signs of a Slowdown
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan -- Taiwan's booming economy shows signs of
a slowdown that could help cool off rampant stock and real
estate speculation and boost slackened industrial production,
officials said.
   But economists warned of an economic recession if the
government fails to take quick measures to stop an exodus of
industries hit by Taiwan's soaring wages, crime and
anti-pollution protests.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The slowdown offers us a good chance to make many
economic and social adjustments," said Chang Hsiu Lien,
deputy director of the government Council for Economic
Planning and Development.
   Taiwan's trade surplus in the first quarter dropped 34.6%
from a year earlier. The index of manufacturing industries'
output in the first two months declined 3% from a year
earlier.
   An Economic Ministry forecast put the 1990 trade surplus
at US$7 billion, down sharply from last year's record $14
billion.
   Mr. Chang said the surplus reduction could help ease
inflationary pressures and stabilize the Taiwan dollar, which
has appreciated more than 50% since 1986 under pressure from
the U.S. to reduce Taiwan's trade surpluses.
   Officials also said they expect that the rampant stock
speculation of the past two years could ease.
   The stock market index has already dropped about 20% in
the past two months to the 10,000-point level. The index
soared from 1,000 points in 1986 to 12,000 late last year, as
cash-rich Taiwanese rushed to make easy money from the
market.
   Soaring land prices could cool off and make it easier for
industries to acquire land for new projects, officials said.
   Officials hope that several important public projects,
including a Taipei mass-transit system and construction of
freeways that were delayed because of soaring land prices and
labor shortages, could be renewed and give the economy a
boost.
   But economists said the 1990 economic growth rate could
fall below 5%, compared with a government-projected 7%.
   "If things do not improve, we can even expect a recession
in a year or two," said Chen Wen Lan, an economist at the
Chunghwa Institute for Economic Research.
   The deteriorating investment climate has triggered an
unprecedented exodus of industries.
   Economists said the overseas relocation of labor-intensive
industries, such as footwear and textiles, could foster the
transition to high-technology industries that are pivotal to
Taiwan's future development. But they fear that other
industries, such as electronics and petrochemicals, also may
follow suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
