<HL>
   Marriott Profit Fell
   39% in First Quarter
   On 3.5% Gain in Sales
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   MHS
</CO>
<IN>
LODGING, HOTELS, MOTELS, LODGES, CAMPGROUNDS (LOD)
EARNINGS (ERN)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Marriott Corp. reported first-quarter
earnings dropped 39%, reflecting continued overcapacity in
the lodging industry.
   Sales for the first quarter increased 3.5% to $1.68
billion, from $1.63 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Net income for the quarter ended March 23 fell to $28
million, or 27 cents a share, compared with $46 million, or
41 cents a share, a year earlier. Results for the
year-earlier quarter included profit from discontinued
operations of $8 million, or seven cents a share, for two
restaurant businesses that are being sold. That quarter also
included $5 million, or five cents a share, from airline
catering operations that were divested in December, and $8
million, or seven cents a share, in lodging transaction
gains.
   Excluding effects of discontinued operations and one-time
gains, Marriott said profit from continuing operations
increased 14% during the 1990 first quarter. Per-share
earnings from continuing operations increased 23% in the
latest quarter, the company said.
   J. W. Marriott Jr., chairman and president, said the
company expects to complete the sale of its Roy Rogers
fast-food restaurant during the 1990 second quarter, and has
received strong interest from potential buyers of its family
restaurant operations.
   Mr. Marriott said lodging operating profit was up 11%,
excluding transaction gains in the year-earlier quarter.
Occupancy for comparable hotels increased 2% to the upper 70%
range. Contract services operating profit was up 19% in the
first quarter, excluding gains from divested airline catering
operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
