<HL>
   Economy:
   Several Large Mall Retailers Report
   Better-Than-Expected Sales for March
   ----
   By Francine Schwadel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   GPS LTD S Z WMT JCP KM DH MA NMG CHH
</CO>
<IN>
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)
SPECIALTY RETAILERS (OTS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Several mall retailers reported better-than-expected sales
for March, given this year's late Easter holiday season.
   Analysts estimate sales at stores open at least a year
rose an average of 3% to 4%, or about the same rate as
inflation. But the analysts said the results suggest April's
showing will be much stronger because of Easter's shift into
April this year from late March. The analysts, who favor
combining the two months for comparison purposes, predict a
same-store increase averaging about 6% for the period.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The numbers show a great deal of underlying strength in
spending," said Margo McGlade of PaineWebber Inc. "In the
beginning of February, most people thought consumer spending
was going to be quite sluggish."
   The March results also suggest that department stores and
mall specialty stores that sell apparel may be gaining market
share. "Malls are doing better than strip centers," said
Thomas Tashjian of Seidler Amdec Securities Inc. "All of the
price promotions and additional advertising in the fourth
quarter has clearly brought consumers back into the mall, and
they are staying there."
   Mr. Tashjian and other analysts noted that mall stores are
ringing up respectable sales gains now, without having to
slash prices as often as they did over the Christmas season.
"There appears to have been a decline in promotional
activity," said Edward Weller of Montgomery Securities.
   Because of a difference in their fiscal calendars, only
about half of the nation's big retailers reported March sales
yesterday. Gap Inc. led the pack with a 12% increase in
same-store sales. Limited Inc.'s same-store sales rose a more
modest 4%, disappointing some analysts.
   Last week, several big retailers, including Sears, Roebuck
&amp; Co., Woolworth Corp. and Montgomery Ward &amp; Co., reported
generally weaker results. Two exceptions were Wal-Mart Stores
Inc. and J.C. Penney Co., where same-store sales rose 12% and
8.7% respectively.
   K mart Corp., a big discount chain, said sales at stores
open at least a year in the U.S. and Canada declined 1.1%. K
mart Chairman Joseph Antonini said "sales were strong in the
first two weeks of March," but "weakened in line with
expectations" because of the late Easter holiday.
   Same-store sales rose 8.2% at Dayton Hudson Corp., which
operates the Target and Mervyn's discount chains in addition
to its Dayton Hudson department store division. At May
Department Stores Inc., same-store sales rose 2.7%. Neiman
Marcus Group Inc.'s same-store sales rose 2.3%. And Carter
Hawley Hale Stores Inc. said its same-store sales declined
2.4%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900413-0104
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900413-0104.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Potomac Watch:
   Regulation Cop
   No Longer
   Walks His Beat
   ----
   By Paul A. Gigot
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<LP>
   The day a story on expanding regulation ran in this
newspaper last November, George Bush sat down at his
typewriter and tapped out a note to chief of staff John
Sununu.
   "Surely we're not re-regulating," the president wrote,
underlining the word for emphasis. "If" -- another underline
-- "it is happening," Mr. Bush added, "maybe I should mention
it at a cabinet meeting."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Well, maybe he should do something.
   Six months after that presidential warning shot, the Bush
administration's re-regulators are back at the barricades.
White House sources not easily given to alarm say they
haven't seen anything like it since the Carter years. Even
discounting for hyperbole, this doesn't sound like the kind
of policy favored by the man who, as vice president, presided
over a task force to slash government red tape.
   The battle is being waged over one of those Washington
jobs that sounds obscure but has real power. It's the White
House Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs. During
the Reagan years, this was the administration's main traffic
cop for regulation, a sanity check on bureaucrats. George
Bush's own task force gave the cop political support in
fights with the Reagan Cabinet.
   Yet in the Bush White House, the cop is off the beat. The
post has been vacant for six months. Budget director Richard
Darman controls the office, but has other things to worry
about. And Sen. John Glenn (D., Ohio) is now pushing
legislation that would strip the office of much of its power.
   Why should anyone care? Consider the bright ideas now
bubbling up from the bureaucracy:
   -- Pedestrians struck by cars are often killed when they
land on the metal hoods. One proposal being studied would
require a rubber hood to cushion the blow, with a sandpaper
surface to keep victims from bouncing far off. Why didn't
Detroit think of that?
   -- The Environmental Protection Agency has ordered cities
to recycle 25% of everything that now goes into incinerators.
Since recycling is difficult and often unpopular, this means
fewer cities will rely on efficient incinerators to dispose
of garbage.
   Instead they'll dump more into landfills, which are
filling up too fast anyway. In any case, isn't this a choice
for the local voters who'll have to do the recycling?
   -- The Department of Transportation wants to require all
new city buses to have wheelchair lifts for the disabled.
Expensive but possibly worth it -- except that DOT also wants
to require cities to provide taxi or van service for any
disabled person who, for a wide variety of reasons, can't
take the bus. Naturally, almost everyone will insist the bus
is somehow inconvenient and opt for a cab.
   -- Another EPA idea would tighten up the already tight
rules for disposing of low-level nuclear waste. This sounds
good, until EPA lists the benefits. It turns out the change
will save from three to 13 cancer deaths over 10,000 years,
with one cancer prevented in the first 500 years.
   Wags have dubbed this the "Christopher Columbus rule,"
since if it had applied in 1492 we'd soon be saving our first
cancer victim.
   -- With EPA Administrator William Reilly off giving
speeches, his minions have floated the possibility of
toughening the nation's "ambient" air-quality standards. One
critic says the new standard for sulfur dioxide pollution is
designed for "an asthmatic, exercising near a power plant,
without medication, during peak emissions."
   -- Agriculture regulators are proposing new rules to
better treat animals in laboratories. Hundreds of millions of
dollars will be diverted from medical research in order to
build new cages and assure that air is recycled more times
each day than even human hospitals require.
   The point isn't that all regulations are this silly.
Obviously many are useful. The point is that without a
traffic cop there's no incentive not to be silly. No
regulator ever got promoted for not regulating. Cabinet
members who show restraint end up being described as a
"disappointment."
   With tax and spend out of fashion, members of Congress now
try to expand their influence through regulation. Every new
rule purports to serve some noble goal, so private-sector
opponents seem selfish. Without an institutional check in the
government, there's no incentive for any restraint at all --
no matter how much a regulation costs.
   Mr. Bush should also be worried about the loss of his own
powers. Killing the regulation cop means reduced control of
the executive branch by the White House. No wonder many on
Capitol Hill want to strip the job of any real power. As just
one example: Sen. Glenn's bill would in effect cancel the
regulatory cop's current power to review paperwork demands
every three years.
   Fortunately, the re-regulation binge is drawing political
flak. U.S. Chamber of Commerce President Richard Lesher
recently sent a letter to President Bush decrying the
"troubling" trend. A bipartisan group of 13 senators --
liberal Arkansas Democrat Dale Bumpers, for one -- has sent
Mr. Glenn a letter urging that the regulatory office not be
gutted. Some White House aides also want Vice President Dan
Quayle's competitiveness council to have the same status that
Mr. Bush's task force had in the Reagan White House.
   Presumably, George Bush believes his work as the
deregulation vice president was worth something. Presumably,
he'd like to consolidate that legacy as president. But on the
evidence so far, he'll have to do more than mention the
subject at a cabinet meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900413-0103
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900413-0103.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Pacific Gas Sheds Nuclear-Plant Woes
   ---
   Accord With Regulators
   Brightens Utility's Outlook
   ----
   By Frederick Rose
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   PCG
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
</IN>
<LP>
   For years, Pacific Gas &amp; Electric Co. suffered the
corporate equivalent of a migraine: a $5.8 billion nuclear
plant reviled by environmentalists and criticized by
regulators.
   The Diablo Canyon facility, nearly 20 years in the making,
became a fixation at PG&amp;E, preoccupying the company's
management and its board. "We were totally absorbed,"
confesses Richard A. Clarke, chairman and chief executive.
"We were worn out."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a striking about face, the nation's largest
investor-owned utility has shed its woes lately, turned
potential financial disaster into a profit, and is trying
hard to rework its tarnished image.
   Thanks to an unconventional pact with state regulators-in
which the company's revenue from Diablo Canyon depends on the
plant's performance rather than a fixed return on investment
-- PG&amp;E last year coaxed $225 million in after-tax profit
from its one-time white elephant and may make more this year
if the plant continues its current output.
   Moreover, the San Francisco-based utility is enjoying
considerable public good will from its quick restoration of
services after the city's Oct. 17 earthquake. The company
expects to recoup nearly all of its estimated $100 million in
earthquake-related outlays from insurance and from rates.
   With regulatory treatment of Diablo Canyon settled, "we
feel liberated," says Mr. Clarke. Now PG&amp;E is wooing the same
environmentalists who once hectored it. It's also striving to
operate Diablo Canyon efficiently and safely, and broaden
investments in non-regulated businesses with which it says it
feels familiar.
   A number of utilities have enjoyed a similar burst of cash
flow, as heavy borrowing for nuclear construction suddenly
has reversed and become a stream of revenue when a plant
comes on line. The sudden wealth has been badly spent in some
cases. Pinnacle West Capital Corp., for instance, squandered
anticipated profits from its Palo Verde nuclear station by
investing in the thrift business, nearly bankrupting itself
in the process.
   PG&amp;E is determined to avoid such pitfalls, says Mr.
Clarke. "We're not diversifying; we're taking advantage of
the business that we know," he asserts.
   Mr. Clarke says the company expects first-quarter net
income to be lower than the year-earlier 53 cents a share. A
scheduled refueling outage of the Unit 2 reactor at the
company's Diablo Canyon nuclear plant makes it "reasonable to
assume that our earnings will be lower than they were last
year," he said.
   But the executive said 1990 net income likely will exceed
the $1.90 a share reported for 1989. However, he said an
average of analysts' estimates of $2.07 a share is "a little
high."
   PG&amp;E had net income of $244.4 million, or 53 cents a
share, in the 1989 first quarter on revenue of $2.11 billion.
Net income last year totaled $900.6 million, or $1.90 a
share, on $8.59 billion in revenue.
   To expand its non-regulated business, Mr. Clarke said PG&amp;E
may substantially boost its investment in natural-gas
exploration and production. The company's PG&amp;E Resources Co.
subsidiary presently holds interests in exploration leases
covering about 600,000 gross acres in Texas, Louisiana,
Arkansas, California, and the Rocky Mountain region. The
holdings amount to about 220,000 acres, net of other
investors' interests.
   "It's not infeasible that in resources you might see a
huge acquisition of reserves," Mr. Clarke added.
   PG&amp;E, late in 1988, acquired Wessely Energy Co.'s U.S. oil
and gas assets for about $100 million. At the time, it said
further acquisitions were planned. However, purchases haven't
materialized yet. Mr. Clarke said the company is constantly
reviewing possibilities.
   In another gas-related venture, PG&amp;E is opening refilling
stations for vehicles powered by compressed natural gas. The
company expects to have nine such stations open to the public
by the end of the year.
   PG&amp;E also plans to about double the capacity of a pipeline
that carries natural gas from western Canada to the Pacific
northwest and California, adding 900 million cubic feet daily
of new transmission capacity. Operation of the $1.5 billion
project is scheduled for 1993. Its capacity is already
contracted for, Mr. Clarke says.
   Jointly, the three natural gas projects are part of an
overall strategy. "Our whole premise is that . . . gas is a
good business to be in," Mr. Clarke says.
   PG&amp;E's environmental thrust is focused on future power
developments, where the company is working at least as hard
on the generating capacity it won't build as that which it
will. Of about 3,300 megawatts of forecast potential new
demand over the next decade, PG&amp;E thinks it can forestall at
least 2,500 megawatts -- roughly equal to the output of two
nuclear generating units -- through energy conservation.
   The utility plans to spend about $170 million this year
and about $200 million annually after that on financial
inducements to reduce demand among a wide range of
electricity consumers. Plans include educational efforts for
energy-efficient lighting, inducements for industry to use
more efficient motors, and better residential insulation
programs.
   The California Public Utility Commission currently is
considering proposals under which PG&amp;E would receive a return
on these investments.
   Mr. Clarke said about 800 megawatts of capacity not
achieved through customer efficiencies may be provided in
part by wind and solar power. A substantial portion, however,
likely will be come from updating existing gas and oil-fired
generating stations, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900413-0102
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900413-0102.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   News Stories on China
   And California Quake
   Win Pulitzer Prizes
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<CO>
   NYTA WPO KRI GCI TMC
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Coverage of political turmoil in China won a
Pulitzer Prize in international reporting for two New York
Times reporters, while two California newspapers were awarded
prizes for their coverage of last year's earthquake.
   The China coverage award was to Nicholas D. Kristof and
Sheryl WuDunn. The San Jose Mercury News, which used
emergency generators to print its post-quake edition, won the
prize for general news reporting. The (Oakland) Tribune photo
staff won the award for spot news photography.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The prizes, recognizing outstanding work in journalism and
the arts, are presented annually by Columbia University.
   Four reporters from the Seattle Times received the
national reporting award for coverage of the Exxon Valdez oil
spill.
   In the arts, playwright August Wilson won his second
Pulitzer Prize for drama ("The Piano Lesson") and novelist
Oscar Hijuelos was cited for fiction ("The Mambo Kings Play
Songs of Love").
   Other arts awards included:
   History: Stanley Karnow, author of "In Our Image:
America's Empire in the Philippines."
   General nonfiction: "And Their Children After Them," by
Dale Maharidge and Michael Williamson, of the Sacramento Bee
newspaper, an examination of the families originally
described in the 1941 book "Let Us Now Praise Famous Men" by
James Agee and Walker Evans.
   Biography: "Machiavelli in Hell," by Sebastian de Grazia.
   Poetry:Charles Simick's "The World Doesn't End."
   Music: Mel Powell, composer of "Duplicates: A Concerto for
Two Pianos and Orchestra."
   Other journalism awards included:
   Public service gold medals: Philadelphia Inquirer, for
reporting on the blood industry, and Washington (N.C.) Daily
News, reporting on carcinogens in the city water supply.
   Investigative reporting: Lou Kilzer and Chris Ison,
Minneapolis-St. Paul Star Tribune, for stories on alleged
profiteering from fires.
   Explanatory journalism: David A. Vise and Steve Coll, the
Washington Post, for stories examining the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
   Specialized reporting: Tamar Stieber, Albuquerque (N.M.)
Journal, for stories linking a rare blood disorder to the
dietary supplement L-tryptophan.
   Feature writing: Dave Curtin, Colorado Springs (Colo.)
Gazette Telegraph.
   Commentary: sports columnist Jim Murray of the Los Angeles
Times.
   Criticism: Allan Temko, San Francisco Chronicle, for
writing on architecture.
   Editorial writing: Thomas J. Hylton, the Mercury
(Pottstown, Pa.); Tom Toles, Buffalo (N.Y.) News, editorial
cartooning.
   Feature photography: David C. Turnley, Detroit Free Press,
photographs of the uprisings in China and Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
