<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Paramount Makes Peace
   With Discount Theaters
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<CO>
   PCI
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   Paramount Pictures made peace with bargain-theater owners
by slightly modifying a pricing formula adopted last summer
that exhibitors said would force them to charge more at the
box office.
   After the policy took effect with the release of
Paramount's "Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade," some
discount movie theaters stopped screening Paramount films.
Now most of them are expected to resume showing Paramount
films without raising prices.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It looks as if the hiatus hurt the theater operators more
than Paramount, one industry observer said.
   Practically speaking, the change will make most Paramount
movies available to discount movie houses four months after
they are released, a month sooner than under last summer's
policy.
   Paramount Communications Inc.'s film unit said the revised
policy strikes a balance that meets discount movie theater
owners' needs and "allows us a fair return on our enormous
investments" in the films. Movie makers have complained that
discount theaters cannibalize first-run theaters. Discounters
say their customers wouldn't be going to the movies at all if
their prices, $1 to $2, weren't so low.
   Paramount's revised pricing formula specifies that films
are available on a percentage of box-office gross basis four
months after theatrical release. The old formula required a
per-capita payment up until 30 days before videocassette
release. Under the per-capita payment requirement, a theater
owner must pay the studio $1.05 for each adult admission (75
cents for children and senior citizens) or 35%, whichever is
higher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900413-0076
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900413-0076.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Census Bureau Admits
   Returns Lagging Badly
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<GV>
COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Census Bureau admitted that returns from
the 1990 census are lagging badly, in part, because Americans
are treating the forms like another piece of junk mail.
   Nearly two weeks after the April 1 target day, the bureau
said only 57% of the 103 million households that were mailed
census forms have returned them. The bureau is hoping for a
minimum 70% return rate by mail. It plans to count the
remaining households in a massive, and costly, household
canvass this spring and summer.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Census Director Barbara Bryant said each 1% of the return
rate that falls below the 70% goal will cost taxpayers an
extra $10 million. The money will be spent to hire and pay
extra door-to-door enumerators. At the same time, census
officials concede that tens of thousands of Americans haven't
received their 1990 population forms due partly to erroneous
mailing lists.
   Census officials were prepared for a poor response rate
from low-income neighborhoods and areas with high immigrant
populations. But Ms. Bryant expressed surprise at the number
of affluent households ignoring their forms.
   "We understand that over the last 10 years, the American
people have been bombarded by direct and junk mail," Ms.
Bryant said. She called the census form "one piece of mail
that counts."
   Population totals from the decennial census are used to
allocate seats in the House of Representatives and state
legislatures. They are also the benchmark for handing out
billions of dollars in government grants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
