900413-0061.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Justice Department Urged
   To Monitor Meat Packers
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   The attorneys general of five Midwestern states urged the
U.S. Justice Department to step up antitrust enforcement in
the meatpacking industry.
   In a letter sent yesterday to U.S. Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh, the state prosecutors cited statistics that they
claim indicate dangerously high concentration of market share
in the meatpacking industry. For example, the state attorneys
general said that the four largest competitors in the
beefpacking industry control about 70% of the fed-cattle
market, up from 39% in 1980.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "For the past decade, antitrust has been the forgotten
area of federal law enforcement," Minnesota's attorney
general, Hubert Humphrey III, said in a statement
accompanying release of the letter. Mr. Humphrey signed the
letter along with his counterparts from Iowa, Montana, North
Dakota and South Dakota.
   A Justice Department spokesman said Mr. Thornburgh hadn't
seen the letter, but that federal prosecutors have "looked at
the meatpacking industry because of the concerns of meat
producers about concentration in that market." The
department's "antitrust division is aware of the situation
and will continue to monitor it," the spokesman added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900413-0060
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900413-0060.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Westwood One Inc.:
   Fiscal First-Quarter Deficit
   Worsened to $7.7 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3A
</SO>
<CO>
   WONE
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Westwood One Inc., Los Angeles, reported that its fiscal
first-quarter loss widened sharply on a rise in revenue
because of increased interest costs, increased investments in
programming, and good-will amortization related to its
acquisition of radio stations in New York and Los Angeles.
   The company, which recently said it is launching its
fourth major radio network, reported a net loss of $7.7
million, or 53 cents a share, compared with a year-earlier
net loss of $3.1 million, or 21 cents a share. Revenue for
the quarter, ended Feb. 28, increased 20% to $31.8 million
from $26.5 million a year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Because of the increased seasonality of its business,
Westwood One said it expected a "significant portion" of its
projected loss for the year to occur in the first quarter.
"As we move into our second quarter, we expect to see
increasing revenues and improved operating results for the
balance of fiscal 1990 from the company's radio networks and
station operations," said William Battison, president and
chief financial officer.
</TEXT>
