<HL>
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet Gets
   Court Support in Rift
   With Unit's Ex-Chief
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   DNB
</CO>
<LP>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- A state court here rejected a request
by software company founder Frank H. Dodge to block Dun &amp;
Bradstreet Corp. and its McCormack &amp; Dodge software unit from
interfering with his efforts to start a new concern.
   In rejecting the request for a preliminary injunction,
Justice Peter M. Lauriat of the Superior Court of
Massachusetts said he wasn't persuaded that Mr. Dodge was
likely to prove his claim of interference by Dun &amp;
Bradstreet. He added that he was unconvinced that Mr. Dodge
would be irreparably harmed without a preliminary injunction.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In addition, Judge Lauriat said, a preliminary injunction
of the scope Mr. Dodge was seeking would "impose a prior
restraint on {Dun &amp; Bradstreet's} protected speech."
   Mr. Dodge had filed a lawsuit contending he was fired
recently without cause by Dun &amp; Bradstreet as president and
chief executive officer of the McCormack &amp; Dodge unit. Thus,
the suit argued, he wasn't bound by an agreement that bars
him from competing against the software company.
   Mr. Dodge and a co-founder sold McCormack &amp; Dodge to Dun &amp;
Bradstreet in 1983, and Mr. Dodge stayed on as president. Dun
&amp; Bradstreet answered that Mr. Dodge resigned and was
therefore subject to the terms of the agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900413-0027
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900413-0027.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   B.F. Goodrich Posts
   69% Decline in Profit
   For the First Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   GR
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<LP>
   AKRON, Ohio -- B.F. Goodrich Co. reported a 69% drop in
first-quarter net income, mainly because of weak prices for
polyvinyl chloride, a plastic that is the company's most
important product. Nonetheless, the profit was somewhat
higher than analysts had expected.
   The plastics, specialty chemicals and aerospace concern
earned $16.2 million, or 56 cents a share, down from a
first-quarter record of $53 million, or $2.02 a share, a year
earlier. The 1989 first-quarter profit includes $2 million
from discontinued operations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales fell 4.2% to $589.8 million from $615.9 million.
   Operating profit from polyvinyl chloride, or PVC, and
related materials dropped 85% to $10.1 million from $68.1
million, on a 22% decline in sales to $272.1 million. Prices
for PVC fell sharply in the 1989 second half and remained
weak until the end of the 1990 first quarter. Meanwhile, the
price of propane, an important feedstock or raw material,
soared following the extremely cold weather in December.
   Operating profit from specialty chemicals rose 33%,
Goodrich said. Aerospace reported a 57% rise in operating
profit, but more than two-thirds of this increase resulted
from reversal of a previously established reserve, following
Goodrich's victory in a patent infringement suit brought by a
competitor.
   Analysts expect a sharp improvement by Goodrich in
subsequent quarters because of rising demand and higher
prices for PVC. Leonard Bogner of Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. said that for 1990, he expects Goodrich to earn $3.75 a
share, which would be a decline from 1989 net of $172.4
million, or $6.48 a share. But last year's results reflected
a first-half boom in PVC, and 1989 profit was partly shielded
from taxes by investment tax-credit carryforwards, which were
exhausted by year end.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Goodrich shares closed at $42.375, up 12.5 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900413-0026
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900413-0026.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   National Intergroup
   Files 2 Suits Against
   Dissident Investors
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   NII
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   PITTSBURGH -- National Intergroup Inc. filed two suits
against dissident investors who have challenged it in a proxy
fight.
   The first suit, filed in U.S. District Court here, asks
that the investors, Centaur Partners and Walker Street
Associates, be forced to divest their holdings in National
Intergroup. Centaur holds 16.5% of NII; together, the two
groups own about 25% of the drug distribution and steel
concern, which is based here.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The suit alleges that the two groups have made materially
false and misleading statements in their solicitation of
proxies. The suit also claims that the two defendants may be
acting together as a group without making required
disclosures.
   The second suit, filed in state court here, seeks a
declaratory judgment that share holdings owned by Walker
Street and its affiliates as well as Centaur's investment
bankers should be attributed to Centaur. If the state court
grants that judgment, National Intergroup said, it will
initiate a rights offering that would decrease the percentage
of its stock owned by the defendants.
   Walker Street Associates had no immediate comment on the
suit. Centaur Partners said it's not acting as a group with
Walker Street or others. Centaur termed the suit an attempt
by National Intergroup to "intimidate us."
</TEXT>
