<HL>
   International:
   Britain's Rate of Inflation
   Jumped to 8.1% in March
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- British inflation jumped to 8.1% in March from
7.5% in February, and the rate for this month is expected to
climb to well over 9%.
   The rate -- the second-highest level since 8.2% in July
1989 -- isn't expected to trigger further tightening in
British base rates, as the trend results largely from earlier
mortgage rate increases and the government's community charge
introduced this month.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But analysts warned that if the government is forced to
increase base rates beyond the current 15% level because of
external reasons, such as a decline in the value of the
pound, the inflation rate could reach double digits this
summer.
   The government blamed the rise largely on the effect of
mortgage rate increases in February. But it said that with
the underlying inflation level, excluding mortgage rates,
rising to 6.3% from 6.2% in February, other factors were at
work, including higher seasonal food prices. It estimated
that annual food inflation alone rose to 8.7% in March -- the
highest level since May 1982 -- from 8.6% in February. Higher
food prices and the community charge, among other factors,
are expected to push inflation higher next month.
   Other government data confirmed that while the economic
slowdown will soon lead to a rise in unemployment for the
first time in nearly four years, wage demands remain high.
Unemployment fell by 6,800 in February, as expected, but this
followed an unusually small decline of 1,700 in January. Wage
settlements continued to rise, with the underlying annual
rate of average earnings boosts jumping to 9.5% in February
from 9.25% in January; a rise to 9.75% is expected by
midsummer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900413-0001
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900413-0001.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Australia's Packer
   Drops Hostile Bid
   For Bond Media Ltd.
</HL>
<DATE>
04/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   A.BOM
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   PERTH -- Australian financier Kerry Packer withdrew a
hostile takeover bid for Bond Media Ltd., a national
television station operator that is part of Alan Bond's
beleaguered corporate empire.
   Mr. Packer sold the network to Bond in 1987 for around 1
billion Australian dollars (US$766 million). He still is owed
A$200 million from that transaction. When it looked as if the
cash-strapped Bond group couldn't repay the debt, Mr. Packer
began a takeover bid for Bond Media that valued the company
at just A$53 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Packer announced in December that he would offer one
share in a new company, Television Corp. of Australia, for
every 10 Bond Media shares. It valued Bond Media at 10 cents
a share -- the stock currently is trading at about 13 cents a
share -- and attracted few acceptances.
   An underwriting agreement arranged by Packer for the bid
expires Sunday. Packer started wind-up, or liquidation
proceedings, on April 6 in the Western Australia state
Supreme Court against Bond Media. The action will be heard
May 2, with an application from Bond Media to have the
petition dismissed.
   Bond Media, meanwhile, is trying to arrange a capital
injection from foreign television companies to reduce debt,
and wants to restructure its finances.
   Separately, Bond Corp. International Ltd., a Hong Kong
unit of Mr. Bond's corporate group, said it concluded the
sale of its interest in Compania de Telefonos de Chile S.A.
for US$388.5 million.
   The company announced in February a preliminary agreement
to sell its 53% stake in Chile's national telephone company
to T.I. Telefonica Internacional de Espana S.A. of Spain.
   Bond Corp. is selling assets to reduce its total debt of
almost A$7 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900413-0022
</DOCNO>
